After the novel coronavirus appeared in Wuhan, China, last December and spread around the world, Trump consistently sought to downplay the danger to the United States, likening coronavirus to the flu and expressing confidence that it could go away once the weather warmed up.
(See our story, “Trump’s Statements About the Coronavirus.”)Only recently has the president begun referring to it as a major problem for the U.S. “This is a pandemic,” he said at a March 17 press conference.
“Three years ago, experts were saying that bat coronaviruses could become a new pandemic,” he said in an email.
“Almost two months ago, experts were saying that the new virus in Wuhan was potentially a global threat.
One of the possible scenarios sketched out included a fast-spreading global disease leading some countries to impose travel bans.